27:06.658 --> 27:09.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, Trump is not going to
come anywhere
near that record, and probably
no other president

27:09.461 --> 27:11.363 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
will either.

27:11.396 --> 27:13.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I would say, certainly on
executive orders,
on the Supreme Court appointment
of Neil Gorsuch,

27:13.498 --> 27:18.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he gets A's in terms of getting
what he wanted
based on some of the promises
that he made

27:18.236 --> 27:19.571 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
during the campaign.

27:19.604 --> 27:22.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael, how do
you see him
compared to others?

27:22.307 --> 27:25.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: I think I
would say it
a little differently, because
Trump made such

27:26.011 --> 27:29.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a point before the campaign just
before the
election, saying, elect me.

27:29.147 --> 27:30.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a referendum on my
100-day action
plan.

27:31.016 --> 27:34.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I will get all these things
through Congress
with a Republican Congress,
which he has had.

27:34.519 --> 27:39.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in retrospect, as you do
say, this has
been 100 days with almost
nothing of great

27:39.524 --> 27:44.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
importance, despite the fact
that he had promised
health care reform and big tax
reform, which

27:44.996 --> 27:49.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he's getting to this week and a
number of
other things, border wall.

27:49.134 --> 27:55.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if you're looking at the 100
days largely
as a legislative standard -- and
that is what

27:55.306 --> 28:01.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is usually is in history --
Trump is really
pretty low down on the list.

28:01.946 --> 28:05.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Barbara,
Michael referenced
where this 100-day standard
comes from, but

28:05.583 --> 28:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how often do presidents get a
lot done early
on in their administration?

28:09.154 --> 28:11.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBARA PERRY: It depends on the
president,
of course.

28:11.122 --> 28:15.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look at someone like
Lyndon Johnson,
who had, of course, two first
days -- first

28:15.293 --> 28:18.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
100 days, one after the Kennedy
assassination,
and then being elected in his
own right, but

28:18.863 --> 28:21.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
particularly after the 1964
election, in 1965,
as he moved forward with the
Great Society,

28:21.800 --> 28:26.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Medicare and Medicaid, and the
Voting Rights
Act of 1965, so we will point to
a president

28:26.104 --> 28:27.439 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like that.

28:27.472 --> 28:29.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, no one will ever again
standard of
FDR in legislation.

28:29.974 --> 28:33.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I also look out where they come
out in the
first 100 days on approval
ratings, which

28:33.311 --> 28:35.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is a fascinating parlor game to
play.

28:35.046 --> 28:35.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know this president coming
in, of course,
came in with the lowest entering
approval

28:35.613 --> 28:37.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
rating of any president.

28:37.382 --> 28:41.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it also doesn't matter
necessarily if
you make a mistake, because the
person with

28:41.486 --> 28:46.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the highest rating after 100
days is John
F. Kennedy, after the Bay of
Pigs.

28:46.091 --> 28:50.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the way he handled that
issue by going
before the American people and
saying, I'm

28:50.261 --> 28:54.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
responsible for this, I'm the
responsible
officer of the government,
caused his approval

28:54.132 --> 28:55.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ratings to spike even further.

28:55.333 --> 28:57.936 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So he comes in with an 83
percent rating.

28:57.969 --> 29:02.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know Trump's approval ratings
is down in
the low 40s at this point.

29:02.073 --> 29:04.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Dig a little
deeper there,
Michael, in terms of how Donald
Trump has

29:04.476 --> 29:06.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
done compared to other
presidents.

29:06.077 --> 29:08.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You started to talk about this a
moment ago
with the setting of the
standard.

29:08.580 --> 29:10.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But how does he stack up?

29:10.348 --> 29:13.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: Well, you
know, a lot of
this, you know, what presidents
do, above

29:13.818 --> 29:17.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and beyond their congressional
record, is,
do they expand the base that
they had on Election

29:17.388 --> 29:18.723 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Day?

29:18.757 --> 29:20.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump, you know, got,
what, 47 percent
of the popular vote.

29:20.625 --> 29:21.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now he is down to about 40,
which would suggest
that, if anything, he's
alienated some of

29:21.326 --> 29:23.061 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the people who voted for him.

29:23.094 --> 29:25.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Usually, with presidents you see
-- and this
is true of almost every
president back to

29:25.730 --> 29:27.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
FDR -- the opposite.

29:27.499 --> 29:30.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They get elected, they say, I
need people
who didn't vote for me, who are
skeptical

29:30.668 --> 29:31.636 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of me.

29:31.669 --> 29:33.004 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm going to reach out to them.

29:33.037 --> 29:34.839 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm the president of all the
people.

29:34.873 --> 29:39.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you see the numbers go up
because people
appreciate the fact that they
are reaching

29:39.277 --> 29:41.045 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
out.

29:41.079 --> 29:44.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is the one thing Donald
Trump -- and
this has been his own choice --
has not done.

29:44.048 --> 29:46.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's essentially said, I'm happy
with my base.

29:46.217 --> 29:47.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I will play to them.

29:48.019 --> 29:52.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I am not going to make a big
effort to reach
out to Democrats and
independents in Congress

29:52.290 --> 29:53.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or out among the American
people.

29:53.491 --> 29:56.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think the numbers show
that he's paid
for that.

29:56.161 --> 30:00.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One other feature
of this presidency
has been his unusual attacks, if
you will,

30:00.865 --> 30:02.634 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Barbara, on the judiciary.

30:02.667 --> 30:06.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Time and again, he has singled
out the courts,
judges, justices when he didn't
like what

30:06.471 --> 30:08.239 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they ruled.

30:08.273 --> 30:11.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA PERRY: He has, which is
a little odd,
in the sense that his sister is
a federal

30:11.109 --> 30:13.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
judge, and a circuit judge at
that.

30:13.111 --> 30:21.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he is following in the
footsteps of some
other presidents, and we can
point directly

30:21.085 --> 30:26.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to FDR, for example, who took on
the judiciary
headlong, not necessarily even
in the first

30:26.324 --> 30:33.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
term, but certainly once he was
reelected
by a landslide in '36, and
famously, or infamously,

30:33.097 --> 30:34.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tried to pack the court.

30:34.999 --> 30:40.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I always go back to a speech
that he gave
in which he said, the two
branches of government,

30:40.471 --> 30:43.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
president and Congress, are
pulling a wagon.

30:43.241 --> 30:48.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are two horses pulling in
the same direction,
and the court, particularly the
Supreme Court,

30:48.813 --> 30:53.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which kept striking down his
many pieces of
New Deal legislation, is pulling
in the opposite

30:53.885 --> 30:55.186 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
direction.

30:55.220 --> 30:56.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was a metaphor that the
American people
could understand.

30:56.921 --> 31:00.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they never supported in the
main or for
the majority his court-packing
plan.

31:00.758 --> 31:02.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, it's not so
unusual, Michael.

31:02.760 --> 31:05.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it is -- there has been a
frequency we
haven't seen.

31:05.496 --> 31:06.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: I think
that's right.

31:06.965 --> 31:08.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And Reagan talked about
unelected judges.

31:08.833 --> 31:12.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in Trump's case, you have
had -- and this
is historically unusual -- two
big executive

31:13.004 --> 31:15.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
orders within these first 100
days, including
most recently sanctuary cities,
and earlier

31:15.607 --> 31:17.308 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the travel ban.

31:17.342 --> 31:19.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Each time, he would say, almost
in anger,
this was something that an
unelected judge

31:19.477 --> 31:21.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
did, or something that a
so-called judge did.

31:21.813 --> 31:27.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's sort of the opposite of
conservatism,
because one of the things that
is most fundamental

31:27.685 --> 31:30.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in being a conservative is
having respect
for the democratic institutions
that we think

31:30.388 --> 31:32.223 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are important.

31:32.257 --> 31:34.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let's talk,
finally, Barbara,
about what the first 100 days
tells us about

31:34.559 --> 31:36.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the rest of a presidency.

31:36.494 --> 31:41.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To what extent can we look at
Donald Trump's
first few months in office and
say this forecasts

31:41.499 --> 31:43.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
whether he's going to be
successful or not?

31:43.501 --> 31:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA PERRY: Well, I'm from
Louisville,
Kentucky, originally, and we're
about to do

31:46.738 --> 31:50.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Kentucky Derby, so I say a
horse can stumble
out of the gate or it can be
running last

31:50.775 --> 31:51.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the first third...

31:51.876 --> 31:52.844 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: Absolutely.

31:52.877 --> 31:55.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA PERRY: ... and still
come on to win.

31:55.146 --> 32:01.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, to the point about low
approval ratings
and Michael's point about not
necessarily

32:01.219 --> 32:08.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
accomplishing all of the list of
things he
said he would do in the 100 days
doesn't mean

32:08.593 --> 32:15.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that he won't be reelected or
that he will
have a failed presidency.

32:15.133 --> 32:20.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you think of someone like
Bill Clinton,
who had a rather chaotic start
in a host of

32:20.438 --> 32:23.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ways in those first 100 days,
and even up
to the Oklahoma City bombing in
1995, and

32:23.875 --> 32:26.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people were saying, oh, it's the
shrinking
presidency and the shrinking
Bill Clinton

32:26.377 --> 32:28.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as president, and yet he came on
strong.

32:28.112 --> 32:31.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we know that he was
reelected in '96.

32:31.449 --> 32:33.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it's not a Ouija board.

32:33.751 --> 32:41.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as a professor, I would say
to the students
in the first third of the
semester, if they

32:41.225 --> 32:46.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
scored lower than they wanted on
the first
test, I would say, you have more
tests to

32:46.564 --> 32:48.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do, you have a term paper,
participate in
class.

32:48.700 --> 32:51.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Trump still has many more
things on which
to be graded.

32:51.536 --> 32:53.571 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
this first...

32:53.604 --> 32:54.572 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

32:54.605 --> 32:56.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: I totally
agree with that.

32:56.507 --> 33:00.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is that it's a standard
that historically
doesn't tell us a lot, because
think of all

33:00.211 --> 33:01.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these presidents and what turns
out to be
important about their
administration, these

33:01.980 --> 33:06.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
moments like Kennedy and the
missile crisis,
or Johnson and the Vietnam
escalation, or

33:06.050 --> 33:07.518 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
George W. Bush and 9/11.

33:07.552 --> 33:10.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
None of those things happened in
the first
-- during the first 100 days.

33:10.989 --> 33:16.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if we were having a great
conversation
like this 100 days into each of
those presidencies,

33:16.160 --> 33:20.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we wouldn't have been able to
predict what
historians now think was really
turning out

33:20.698 --> 33:22.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to be pivotal.

33:22.066 --> 33:24.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael
Beschloss, Barbara
Perry, thank you both.

33:24.335 --> 33:25.803 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: Thank you,
Judy.

33:25.837 --> 33:27.638 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA PERRY: Thank you, Judy.

33:27.672 --> 33:31.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, tomorrow, we
will take
a look at the Trump
administration's successes

33:31.142 --> 33:33.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and setbacks overseas within its
first 100
days.

33:33.177 --> 33:37.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now a look at a new film about
the brutal
Syrian civil war.

33:37.148 --> 33:38.950 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has that story.

33:38.983 --> 33:41.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The French
government said
today its analysis of samples
from a chemical

33:41.652 --> 33:44.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attack in Syria earlier this
month prove that
the government of Bashar
al-Assad was responsible.

33:44.222 --> 33:47.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That attack was one more flash
point in a
war that has now entered its
seventh year,

33:47.325 --> 33:52.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and it is the subject of a
searing new documentary
called "Hell on Earth: The Fall
of Syria and

33:52.296 --> 33:54.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Rise of ISIS."

33:54.098 --> 33:59.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It debuts at the Tribeca Film
Festival this
week here in New York, and will
air later

33:59.170 --> 34:01.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
this summer on National
Geographic.

34:01.039 --> 34:03.741 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It is co-directed by the
journalist and author
Sebastian Junger, who also
narrates the film.

34:03.775 --> 34:05.576 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thanks for joining us.

34:05.610 --> 34:07.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER, Director,
"Hell on Earth:
The Fall of Syria and the Rise
of ISIS": Thank

34:08.012 --> 34:08.980 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

34:09.013 --> 34:10.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Why make this
right now?

34:10.114 --> 34:11.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: We started
about two years
ago.

34:11.916 --> 34:24.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We wanted to explain why the
Syrian civil
war happened, how it evolved,
and particularly

34:24.429 --> 34:32.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
why ISIS came out of it.

34:32.637 --> 34:35.973 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ISIS is a kind of rare
phenomenon.

34:36.007 --> 34:38.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we wanted to explain that to
the American
people.

34:38.342 --> 34:41.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But there's a
family that
you intersperse throughout this
documentary.

34:41.712 --> 34:46.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are making their way out of
Syria, or
attempting to as they go along.

34:46.317 --> 34:52.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's a real telling clip
early on in
the film where there's a father
just trying

34:52.423 --> 34:54.025 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to comfort his kids.

34:54.058 --> 34:55.593 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Take a look.

34:55.626 --> 34:59.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): Don't
be afraid,
dear.

34:59.297 --> 35:00.832 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Don't be afraid.

35:00.865 --> 35:02.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(CRYING)

35:02.166 --> 35:05.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator):
Honestly, I'm about
to explode.

35:05.636 --> 35:10.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I can't express what is
happening inside of
me.

35:10.374 --> 35:15.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have to smile against my will,
so the kids
don't get scared.

35:15.246 --> 35:19.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
